# DeepWind — Claude Code conventions starter

This file is a starter `CLAUDE.md` for projects adopting the DeepWind conventions
that ship via `curl -fsSL https://pm-33.com/install | bash`.

Copy this into the root of your project (or merge into your existing
`CLAUDE.md`) so every Claude Code session in this project picks up the
shared rules.

---

## Harness discipline

For any work estimated at **16+ hours across 3+ sessions** with **3+ logical
phases**, prefer a harness project over a single-session task. The harness
framework lives at `~/deepwind-frameworks/` (installed by the DeepWind bundle).

- Use the `harness-discovery` skill for initial scoping.
- Use the `harness-planner` skill (or `harness-planner-agent`) to break the
  project into phased tasks.
- Use the `harness-coordinator` agent for any session that's orchestrating
  multi-specialist work. The coordinator **never** writes code directly —
  it dispatches specialists via the Task tool.
- Specialists run the `harness-discipline` skill: per-agent git worktrees,
  TDD discipline (RED → GREEN → REFACTOR → DELIVERY), evidence on every
  step.

For one-shot work (<8 hrs, single phase), just do the work directly. The
harness is overhead that pays back over multi-session projects, not under
them.

## Multi-specialist spec review

Before implementing any non-trivial spec, run the **`gauntlet-review`**
skill. Different specialists (backend, security, performance, AI engineer,
etc.) review the same spec adversarially and surface problems primary
implementers tend to miss.

Trigger: say *"gauntlet review this spec"* (with the spec path) and the
skill orchestrates the parallel review.

## DeepWind MCP tool usage

**BEFORE the first `mcp__pm33-staging__pm33_*` tool call in a session,
invoke `Skill({ skill: "deepwind-mcp" })`.** That skill (installed by the DeepWind
bundle into `~/.claude/skills/pm33-mcp/`) captures tool routing, the 9
known gaps (5000-char description cap, `score_alignment` is keyword-only,
MCP intermittent disconnect, etc.), batch-creation patterns, canonical
parent UUIDs, and the queue-and-execute pattern for MCP instability.

Skip the invoke only if you've already loaded the skill earlier in the
same session. The skill is cheap to read and prevents repeated rediscovery
of conventions.

Common tools after loading the skill:
- `pm33_create_work_item` — bug fixes, features, improvements
- `pm33_create_brief` — agent-dispatched structured units (preferred over
  `create_work_item type='story'` for AI-executable work)
- `pm33_create_idea` — backlog items not yet committed
- `pm33_update_work_item` — bump priority, link to parent epic, change description
- `pm33_query_backlog` — find existing items before duplicating

If the DeepWind MCP isn't connected, type `/mcp` in Claude Code and authenticate
to **claude.ai DeepWind** — then restart the session so the `mcp__pm33-staging__*`
tools register.

## Test execution discipline

- **Run tests locally**, never via SSH (SSH sessions hang).
- Default test runner per project varies; prefer the project's `npm test`
  / `pytest` / etc. wrapper script if one exists.
- Don't run more than 2 concurrent test-node processes on a dev machine.
- Clean up hung processes after a test session
  (`pkill -f "vitest|playwright|jest"` if needed).

## Git: stage explicit paths

When multiple Claude Code sessions or agents may be running concurrently,
never use `git add .` or `git add -A` — they sweep up files from other
agents. Always stage exact paths:

```
git add path/to/file1.ts path/to/file2.ts
```

For full multi-agent isolation, use per-agent git worktrees (the
`harness-discipline` skill walks through the setup).

## Honesty over confidence

When a tool result conflicts with your assumption, trust the tool result
and revise. When you're not sure, say "I don't know" or "I haven't
verified" instead of pattern-matching from prior context. Particularly for:

- Schema state (always re-check `\d <table>` if there's any doubt)
- Deploy status (always re-check Vercel/Railway status, never assume)
- Branch state (always re-check `git log origin/main` vs local)

The cost of a wrong-but-confident answer compounds across the session;
the cost of "let me re-verify" is one tool call.

---

**This is a starter file.** Edit, extend, or replace as your project's
conventions evolve. DeepWind's full reference `CLAUDE.md` lives in the
pm-33-core repo and is not bundled — it contains many project-specific
rules that don't generalize.
